<h2>A standard production timeline</h2>
<p>Here's how a typical build breaks down from kickoff to shipping:</p>
<div class="spec-table">
  <div class="r"><span class="l">File preparation, scaling &amp; planning</span><span class="v">Day 1–3</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Fabrication — 3D printing, CNC, laser cutting</span><span class="v">Day 4–10</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Painting, detailing &amp; assembly</span><span class="v">Day 11–18</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Lighting installation &amp; base work</span><span class="v">Day 19–22</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Quality control &amp; photo review</span><span class="v">Day 23–24</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Packing &amp; shipping</span><span class="v">Day 25</span></div>
</div>
<h2>What affects your timeline</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Complexity and scale</strong> — larger, multi-building models take longer to fabricate and assemble.</li>
<li><strong>Level of detail</strong> — fine finishes, landscaping, and lighting add production time.</li>
<li><strong>Revisions</strong> — changes after fabrication has started extend the schedule.</li>
<li><strong>Special features</strong> — electronics, moving parts, and modular elements require additional build and test time.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Plan ahead</h2>
<p>Deadlines compress quickly — earlier is always better. Whether you need a fast concept study or a highly detailed presentation model, early coordination produces the best results.</p>
